# Global Trivy ignore configuration for CI pipelines.
#
# This file ships in the pipelines repo and is ALWAYS applied. At scan time each
# project's own root `.trivyignore` (if present) is APPENDED to it -- see
# `global/scripts/tools/trivy/run.sh` and `run-sca.sh`, which build a merged
# ignore file and pass it to Trivy via `--ignorefile`. This mirrors the global +
# repo merge already used for `.golangci.yml` and `.gitleaks.toml`: curate
# fleet-wide, well-understood false positives here so every consumer inherits
# them, while projects add repo-specific entries in their own `.trivyignore`
# without losing these.
#
# Add one Trivy finding ID per line (`#` starts a comment). Every entry MUST be
# justified with a comment: what it is, why it's safe to ignore here, and when to
# revisit. See:
# https://aquasecurity.github.io/trivy/latest/docs/configuration/filtering/#by-finding-ids

# GO-2026-5932 -- golang.org/x/crypto/openpgp deprecation (advisory published 2026-07-07).
# The openpgp subpackage is unmaintained/unsafe upstream with NO fixed version. Trivy's
# gomod scanner flags the whole `golang.org/x/crypto` MODULE, but our Go services depend
# on x/crypto only for ssh / hashing / cipher primitives and never import openpgp
# (verified: `go mod why golang.org/x/crypto/openpgp` -> "does not need package", and the
# reachability-aware `sca:govulncheck` job passes). It is a module-level false positive;
# govulncheck remains the authoritative Go SCA gate. REVISIT if any repo genuinely adopts
# OpenPGP -- then migrate to github.com/ProtonMail/go-crypto/openpgp rather than relying on
# this ignore.
GO-2026-5932
